    "120559687": {
      "title": "Equations with a difference kernel on a finite interval",
      "abstract": "ContentsIntroduction CHAPTER 1. Invertible operators with a difference kernel \u00a7 1. Construction of the inverse operator \u00a7 2. Existence conditions and the structure of the inverse operator \u00a7 3. Equations with a special right-hand side \u00a7 4. Operators with difference kernel in the space CHAPTER 2. Equations of the first kind with a difference kernel \u00a7 1. Equations of the first kind with a special right-hand side \u00a7 2. Solution of equations of the first kind \u00a7 3. Examples \u00a7 4. Generalized solutions \u00a7 5. Regularization CHAPTER 3. Applied problems leading to equations with a difference kernel \u00a7 1. The equations of the contact theory of elasticity \u00a7 2. The problem of optimal prediction \u00a7 3. The problem of diffraction on a strip \u00a7 4. On certain problems of hydrodynamics \u00a7 5. Extremal problems in the theory of synthesis of antennae CHAPTER 4. Mathematical problems leading to equations with a difference kernel \u00a7 1. Factorization of operators \u00a7 2. Reduction of a class of Volterra operators to their simplest form \u00a7 3. Inverse problems References"
    },
    "36774415": {
      "title": "Effect of nonlinearity on the steady motion of a twinning dislocation",
      "abstract": "Abstract We consider the steady motion of a twinning dislocation in a Frenkel\u2013Kontorova lattice with a double-well substrate potential that has a non-degenerate spinodal region. Semi-analytical traveling wave solutions are constructed for the piecewise quadratic potential, and their stability and further effects of nonlinearity are investigated numerically. We show that the width of the spinodal region and the nonlinearity of the potential have a significant effect on the dislocation kinetics, resulting in stable steady motion in some low-velocity intervals and lower propagation stress. We also conjecture that a stable steady propagation must correspond to an increasing portion of the kinetic relation between the applied stress and dislocation velocity."
    }
